    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-04-18T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-04-18T03:00:00-05:00" n="803"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d803">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">684A.86/4–1854: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 803<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Iraq (<persName corresp="#p_BBY1"
                            type="from">Berry</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d803fn1">Repeated to Amman, Beirut, Cairo, Damascus, Jidda,
                        Tel Aviv, Jerusalem, London, and Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-04-18T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 18, 1954—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>623. Regarding <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 574, April 15.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d803fn2">Printed as telegram 407 to Amman, <ref target="#d796"
                            >Document 796</ref>.</note> As seen from Baghdad Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName>’s suggested course of action to “nibble at
                    edges of problem seeking first frontier control” is most feasible approach. At
                    local level without benefit of wide publicity we can make progress even on
                    Palestine problem whereas when issues are spotlighted both sides take inflexible
                    positions.</p>
                <p>Unfortunately, Iraqis are convinced that actions looking toward getting the Arabs
                    and Israelis together in <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> at high level is
                    Zionist inspired to meet Israeli needs. Unfortunately, too, the greater the
                    pressure to bring about such a meeting the greater resistance set up.</p>
                <p>As for getting parties together through other means, Embassy suggests that
                    failure to act through <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> would convince Arabs
                    that western powers share Arabs lack of confidence in <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> and therefore by-pass it when it does not serve their interests.
                    Embassy not in position to comment fruitfully on (2) since it has had no direct
                    experience with these problems.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BBY1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berry</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
